doc.previous: The principal court is the Royal Court with appeals to the Jersey Court of Appeal and ultimately to the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council The Bailiff is head of the judiciary the Bailiff and the Deputy Bailiff are appointed by the Crown Other members of the island s judiciary are appointed by the Bailiff
doc.after: Administratively Jersey is divided into twelve parishes All border on the sea They were named after the Christian saints to whom their ancient parish churches were dedicated  The parishes of Jersey are further divided into vingtaines or in St Ouen cueillettes divisions that are historic Today they are used chiefly for purposes of local administration and electoral constituency
